1116709679235764226.text: Every year since, whenever I hear about new Star Wars news, and especially anything about the #StarWarsCelebration, I think about the night I stumbled upon a SWC after party and danced my heart out with SW fans. It was the start to a pretty good trip.

1116709678564745216.text: Again recall that at the time, I had zero interest in the Star Wars franchise. I didn't even know what to expect from this crowd. But a few vodka cranberries later, the party was popping. Much to my surprise, these Star Wars fans could get down and I had a blast. Go figure.

1116709677805518848.text: I got there pretty early so there were a few wallflowers milling about and the DJs were just settling into a groove. I made sure to befriend the open bar staff. It wasn't long before tons of other Star Wars fans started pouring in and the party got off proper.

1116709677168037888.text: This was at least, 2005? I had no idea Star Wars had a "celebration" of any kind, but apparently I booked my trip during that year's event. And they were having an after party in my hotel. I wasn't a Star Wars fan at the time, but I sure was a fan of an open bar and dancefloor.

1116709676530450437.text: I asked a man outside the room what the party was for. I had no clue what event could be going on during the week that would call for a dance party. He said, "Oh, this is for the #StarWarsCelebration. You can come in if you want." I had no idea what he was talking about.

1116709675892969473.text: I wasn't aware of any plans scheduled at my hotel that evening so I was surprised to hear thumping tunes and a few people hanging outside a ballroom. I went to investigate, eager to at least party for a bit before retiring to my room.

1096198770004504576.text: It'll take some time to land back on your feet, but when you do, remember that you're starting fresh and your new job is NOT your old job. Best of luck to anyone struggling right now. I've been there, more than once! But you can bounce back.

1096198768234504198.text: I know being letting go can be tough and when it happens, it can feel like a whirlwind. Don't ever beat yourself up for it. Don't feel minimized because your livelihood got turned upside based on a business decision. Keep your chin up and get support from pals.

1096198767227879425.text: Been at Polygon for the past three years now. Our union, @vox_union, is filled with incredibly smart and dedicated people looking out for all of us. I couldn't ask for better support. It seems so extraordinary what they do, but everyone deserves support like theirs.

1096198766477090817.text: Was hired by another agency shortly after but we parted ways once we both realized it wasn't a good fit for either of us. Fun short run, but just wasn't a fit. Got trapped in a room with 2Chainz during that job though.

1096198764728107008.text: I freelanced at an agency through a headhunter. The agency liked me so much they hired me indefinitely. I got let go when the entire agency folded. Again, not really my fault. I wasn't given any severance, but I wasn't expecting one either as a freelancer / consultant.

1096198763868237824.text: Our director cried because she hated having to let me go. It made sense to drop me, but it upset her that she had to do it because she believed in me. It's a great agency and don't hold any ill will against them. They let me go properly.

1096198762173739008.text: I get let go at an agency through no fault of my own. My team's director left. Then my direct boss left. They kept me on for a while but since I didn't fit into any other teams, I was let go. I got severance, got reimbursed for a new computer I bought with my own money, and more.

1096198761393602560.text: I wasn't given any severance, payouts, or respect the whole time I was there. For the amount of work I did there, I was severely underpaid. I got yelled at for asking for a raise. Director complained they took a pay cut to work there and that was that.

1096198759883702273.text: When I found a job before the month was over - and I gave them two weeks - they ignored me for those two weeks. And both of my bosses were not in the office on my final day. I had to slip my key under the door. They also bugged me over Xmas break to make exit documents for them.

1096198758747066368.text: I worked at a non-profit that treated myself and everyone so poorly they made an intern cry and legitimately made me think I had a learning disability. They gave me about a month notice letting me know I was going to be let go, but I could look for jobs while there...

1096198757882966016.text: I DJed for years in NYC across several bars and lounges for a living about a decade ago. I started burning out and probably started phoning it in. The main folks who hired me across a few bars let me go by having my friend, a fellow DJ, let me know that I was through.

1096198756977049602.text: I was underpaid and hated what I did. I got unemployment and still lived at home so it didn't hit me very hard. I was actually thrilled to be let go.

1096198756121366528.text: Very first time it was one of the worst days of my life. I was crying so much on the ride to work, I had to pull over. Then, I walked in and 95% of the company got laid off. I was so young at the time, I didn't even think to ask about severance.

1096198754737242112.text: Did you know I'm a very smart cookie that's been laid off and let go few times? It isn't fun, it gets to you, and sometimes it derails your life suddenly. Here's a thread about all the times it's happened to me.

1081572498641166338.text: Lisa Ling is also world class at this and everyone should devour her shows. It's just refreshing to explore the same premise of these shows but with a perspective we hardly ever see represented in these programs.

1081571903163256838.text: Louis Theroux is also great at this. While most of his documentaries are targeted at niche and divisive communities, he always tries to go in judgement free. He's always eager to explore how they operate and why they are the way they are. He offers observation, not opinion.

1081569030903869440.text: The "fish out of water" premise has its merits though. It can be interesting seeing someone grapple with a new reality and acclimate to it to better understand it. That transition should say something interesting and the other culture shouldn't be the butt of a joke however.

1081568318987923456.text: This is why I respected folks like Bourdain. An expert in his field, but still visited every place whether it was another borough of his city or a back alley across the world with child's eyes. He respected the history and culture of a place and tried to understand its origin.

1081568318081896449.text: To be clear, I love cultural tourism shows. I like understanding cultures I've yet to experience and appreciate myself. But other peoples' NORMAL shouldn't be viewed as WEIRD or EXOTIC. Gawking at the everyday lives of others is so fucking gross.
